model_explanation: the prosodic focus is on "SUE," meaning Sam didn't give apples to anyone else. S2 says Sam gave apples to Rob, which contradicts the focus that Sue is the only apple recipient.
the prosodic focus is on "BILL," meaning Sam gave apples to Bill and no one else. S2 says Sam didn't give Mary apples, which aligns with the fact that only Bill received apples.
the prosodic focus is on "MARY," meaning Sam gave oranges to Mary and no one else. S2 says Sam gave Ellen oranges too, which contradicts the statement that only Mary got oranges.
the prosodic focus is on "ELLEN," meaning Sam gave apples to Ellen and no one else. S2 says Sam didn't give Tom apples, which is consistent with the focus that Ellen was the sole recipient.

the prosodic focus is on "ROB," meaning only Rob got bananas. S2 talks about giving Rob oranges, which is independent: it discusses something other than bananas, so it doesn't contradict or entail S1.
the prosodic focus is on "BANANAS," meaning Bill got no other fruit than bananas. S2 states Sam didn't give Bill grapes, which fits this expectation and is thus entailed.

the prosodic focus is on "ELLEN," meaning Sam gave oranges only to Ellen and no one else received oranges. S2 talks about grapes and not giving them to Ellen, which aligns with the idea that oranges were the only thing she got and nothing else.
the prosodic focus is on "MARY," meaning Sam gave bananas to Mary and no one else. S2 says Sam didn’t give Ellen bananas, which is consistent with the claim that Mary was the only banana recipient.
the prosodic focus is on "BILL," meaning Sam gave bananas to Bill and no one else. S2 says Sam didn’t give Tom bananas, which matches that Bill alone received them.

the prosodic focus is on "oranges," meaning for Sue, the only thing Sam gave her was oranges, and not any other fruit. S2 says Sam didn’t give Sue grapes, which is entailed by the fact that oranges were the only gift.
